                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d477">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">701.9493/89: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-05-11T13:00:00+08:00"
                            >May 11, 1935—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received May 11—5:58 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>100. Hsu Mo<note n="9" xml:id="d477fn9">Chinese vice Minister for Foreign
                        Affairs.</note> stated to me this morning over the telephone that in a very
                    short time the Chinese Legation in Tokyo and the Japanese Legation in China
                    would be raised to the status of embassies. He asked that this information be
                    treated as confidential and that if the American Government should decide to
                    take similar action with respect to its Legation in China, the Chinese
                    Government would be as pleased as it was with the decision of the Japanese
                    Government.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
